Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'll pretend to still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can manage to open this damned file. (Fucking OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm here.
And that's when it starts drilling really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier all the way up makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like wood shavings, so it's justified even if it's an anti-mask. And besides, I really need to protect myself, right?
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The positive thing is that I finally finished re-reading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but there's a big twist. Good job.
In the process of doing find-replace on … ➡️  ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I stick to it. The most natural-sounding speeches are usually fragmented, especially when people let their emotions run free.
The artisan is dusting off with the vacuum cleaner; hopefully, he will have finished soon.
I heard him go out (to do something). So I took a look to see where he was at. It's far from done :(<s>
Only 7 more pages for Chapter Five. It remains my favorite chapter, and it's rather polished. A few formatting changes, and minor adjustments to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I would like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still fiddling in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The artisan has left!
He told me he had done a quote for the whole floor, but the owners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged corner near the door. It's definitely better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
